  "articleSummary": "The article argues that PostgreSQL already provides three distinct, native search primitives—full‑text search (lexical tsvector + GIN), trigram similarity (pg_trgm), and exact‑match indexes (B‑tree/hash)—and that teams should combine them rather than defaulting to a single tool or an external search service. It explains when each primitive is the right fit: full‑text for long prose with stemming and ranking, trigrams for fuzzy name or typo‑tolerant matching, and exact indexes for binary‑answer fields like IDs or emails. The guide is written as a practical tutorial for developers and DBAs, using a “tool‑map” metaphor that frames search as choosing the appropriate primitive based on input shape and query intent.",
